    "name": "Question 13 @ 2022/2023",
    "Question": {
      "content": "Kirchhoff's first rule is:",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "ΣI=0",
        "ΣR=0",
        "ΣI R=0",
        "ΣI=0"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "ΣI=0"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<div style='font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;'><h3 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Kirchhoff's Current Law (KCL)</h3><p>Kirchhoff's first rule, or the <strong>junction rule</strong>, states:</p><p style='background: #f8f9fa; padding: 10px; border-left: 4px solid #3498db;'><strong>ΣI<sub>in</sub> = ΣI<sub>out</sub></strong> or equivalently <strong>ΣI = 0</strong> (with sign convention)</p><h4 style='color: #2c3e50; margin-top: 15px;'>Key Implications:</h4><ul><li>Charge conservation at circuit junctions</li><li>Current entering = current leaving</li><li>Applies to <em>all</em> junctions in a circuit</li></ul><h4 style='color: #2c3e50;'>Common Misconceptions:</h4><ul><li><strong>ΣR=0</strong>: No physical meaning in circuit laws</li><li><strong>ΣIR=0</strong>: Relates to Kirchhoff's <em>second</em> rule (voltage law)</li></ul></div>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Kirchhoff's Laws",
      "DC Circuits",
      "Electric Current"
    ]
